<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
      Hardened-runtime entitlements for the notarized Developer ID build.

      Notarization (Apple, since macOS 10.14) REQUIRES the hardened runtime
      (codesign `--options runtime`). The hardened runtime turns on library
      validation by default: a process may then only load dylibs signed by
      Apple or by the same Team ID as the host binary.

      The Recall Desktop SDK we bundle does NOT satisfy that: its
      GStreamer.framework dylibs (~100 of them) and the top-level Recall
      dylibs (liblibbot_desktop_rs.dylib, libui_recorder.dylib) carry no
      Team ID. The process that loads them is the SDK's own child binary
      `desktop_sdk_macos_exe` (otool shows it links
      @rpath/GStreamer.framework/Versions/1.0/GStreamer). We re-sign that
      binary ourselves in scripts/sign-bundle.sh Phase 5, so attaching this
      entitlement THERE is exactly what lets it dlopen the Team-ID-less
      GStreamer dylibs under the hardened runtime instead of SIGABRT-looping.

      scripts/sign-bundle.sh applies the signing flags (including
      --entitlements) to every component it signs, so this lands on
      desktop_sdk_macos_exe, the main hq-sync-menubar binary, and the
      sidecar shim alike. That is harmless for the main binary (all its
      deps are static Rust + Apple system frameworks) and load-bearing for
      desktop_sdk_macos_exe.

      Kept intentionally minimal: the app is NOT sandboxed, so microphone /
      screen-recording / accessibility access flow through TCC + the
      Info.plist usage strings at runtime, not through sandbox entitlements.
      The bridge sets no DYLD_* environment variables and resolves the
      framework purely via baked-in @rpath, so allow-dyld-environment-
      variables is deliberately omitted. Add entitlements here only if the
      dry-run notarization / launch surfaces a concrete need.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
